thickness do not exceed that of

00:08:21.485 --> 00:08:23.720
a single Particle of Oil."
 

00:08:23.720 --> 00:08:29.444
(Imagine Newton,
350 years ago or 300 years ago

00:08:29.444 --> 00:08:35.419
here, thinking about a single
particle of oil.

00:08:35.419 --> 00:08:40.649
Could he possibly measure that?
 

00:08:40.649 --> 00:08:42.549
We'll think about that later.
 

00:08:42.549 --> 00:08:44.168
Okay.)
 

00:08:44.168 --> 00:08:47.883
"There are therefore
Agents in Nature able to make

00:08:47.883 --> 00:08:51.458
the Particles of Bodies stick
together by very strong

00:08:51.458 --> 00:08:52.558
Attractions.
 

00:08:52.558 --> 00:08:56.663
And it is the business of
experimental Philosophy to find

00:08:56.663 --> 00:08:57.908
them out."
 

00:08:57.908 --> 00:09:01.182
That's what we need to
find, what is it that holds

00:09:01.182 --> 00:09:02.759
these particles together?
 

00:09:02.759 --> 00:09:05.390
"Experimental
philosophy"

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:06.629
means science.
 

00:09:06.629 --> 00:09:09.697
And we're going to engage in
this business,

00:09:09.697 --> 00:09:13.936
and it'll take us about five
weeks to figure out what it is

00:09:13.936 --> 00:09:16.639
that holds these things
together.

00:09:16.639 --> 00:09:19.402
Now, let's just look,
from physics,

00:09:19.402 --> 00:09:24.437
at the amount of binding energy
you get from different kinds of

00:09:24.437 --> 00:09:25.168
laws.
 

00:09:25.168 --> 00:09:27.817
First there's Coulomb's law;
so it charges over the

00:09:27.817 --> 00:09:28.399
distance.
 

00:09:28.399 --> 00:09:30.690
I think you all know that one.
 

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:34.610
Then there's magnetic
interaction, two magnetic

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:39.639
dipoles, and the energy is
1/r^3, falls off very rapidly.

00:09:39.639 --> 00:09:41.703
Then there's the
"strong"

00:09:41.703 --> 00:09:45.529
binding that holds particles
together in the nuclei of atoms.

00:09:45.529 --> 00:09:48.840
And gravitation, of course.
 

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:51.009
And the chemical bond.
 

00:09:51.009 --> 00:09:54.707
So here's a scale of energies,
and we use, in this course,

00:09:54.707 --> 00:09:56.914
the old fashioned
kilocalories/mol,

00:09:56.914 --> 00:10:00.028
which American organic chemists
like to use.

00:10:00.028 --> 00:10:02.759
Some day it'll change to
kilojoules/mol,

00:10:02.759 --> 00:10:05.629
but for me it's still
kilocalories/mol.

00:10:05.629 --> 00:10:08.977
Okay, this is a logarithmic
scale, so it covers a very wide

00:10:08.977 --> 00:10:09.440
range.
 

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:11.664
Now Coulomb,
if you have a proton and an

00:10:11.664 --> 00:10:14.347
electron,
as far apart as the distance of

00:10:14.347 --> 00:10:17.986
the carbon-carbon bond,
that's 216 kilocalories/mol,

00:10:17.986 --> 00:10:21.428
right in the middle of this,
or near the middle.

00:10:21.428 --> 00:10:24.269
Magnetic interaction is much
weaker.

00:10:24.269 --> 00:10:28.730
If you have two electron spins,
at the same distance from one

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:31.110
another, their energy is what?
 

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:35.793
One, two, three,
four, five orders of magnitude

00:10:35.793 --> 00:10:38.440
smaller, 10^5th smaller.
 

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:40.708
The "strong"
binding that holds a proton and

00:10:40.708 --> 00:10:42.850
a neutron together is in the
deuterium nucleus,

00:10:42.850 --> 00:10:46.950
that is within the nucleus,
not at 1.54 Ångstroms,

00:10:46.950 --> 00:10:52.070
is 10^5th stronger than
Coulombic interaction.

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:55.019
And gravity is ever so much
weaker.

00:10:55.019 --> 00:10:58.836
If you had two carbon atoms,
that were at that distance,

00:10:58.836 --> 00:11:02.028
the energy would be 10^-32
kilocalories/mol.

00:11:02.028 --> 00:11:06.210
So forget gravity as a way of
holding things together.

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:11.956
But then we have Coulombic up
or down by 5 orders of

00:11:11.956 --> 00:11:13.309
magnitude.
 

00:11:13.309 --> 00:11:16.548
Now what is a chemical bond;
how strong is it?

00:11:16.548 --> 00:11:20.888
A chemical bond is about -- the
carbon-carbon bond is about 90

00:11:20.888 --> 00:11:22.240
kilocalories/mol.
 

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:26.110
So not so far from the Coulomb
energy, from electrostatic

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:27.009
attraction.
 

00:11:27.009 --> 00:11:30.216
So maybe this hints that
electrostatic attraction has

00:11:30.216 --> 00:11:31.820
something to do with it.
 

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:34.548
But maybe not,
maybe it's something entirely

00:11:34.548 --> 00:11:34.928
new.
 

00:11:34.928 --> 00:11:40.590
And we haven't talked about
kinetic energy.

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:43.990
Does that have anything to do
with the strength of the bond?

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:47.269
So we'll get back to that later
on.

00:11:47.269 --> 00:11:51.707
Okay, so is there a chemical
force law, the thing that Newton

00:11:51.707 --> 00:11:53.038
was looking for?
 

00:11:53.038 --> 00:11:55.288
Now here's an interesting way
to phrase that.

00:11:55.288 --> 00:11:58.937
Suppose you had a chain of
atoms, a thread that was single

00:11:58.937 --> 00:12:02.840
atoms bonded to one another,
and you started stretching it.

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:07.668
It would stretch,
and at some point it would pop.

00:12:07.668 --> 00:12:11.206
Now let's just take three of
the atoms and we'll put stiff

00:12:11.206 --> 00:12:14.620
rods on the outer ones and we'll
start stretching it.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:22.182
So it'll stretch,
stretch, stretch,

00:12:22.182 --> 00:12:25.519
stretch, pop.
 

00:12:25.519 --> 00:12:30.720
Now the question is how far do
you stretch it before it pops?

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:34.928
What determines how far you
stretch it before it pops?

00:12:34.928 --> 00:12:38.636
Okay, this must have to do with
the force law between atoms,

00:12:38.636 --> 00:12:42.029
which then will have to do with
molecular structure.

00:12:42.029 --> 00:12:44.958
So it could be like springs,
Hooke's law,

00:12:44.958 --> 00:12:47.009
Ut tensio,
sic vis.

00:12:47.009 --> 00:12:48.695
Okay, so the force is
proportional to the

00:12:48.695 --> 00:12:51.066
displacement,
and the energy to the square of

00:12:51.066 --> 00:12:53.200
the displacement and the energy
then,

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:55.330
the potential energy,
is a parabola.

00:12:55.330 --> 00:12:57.770
We define zero when they're at
the standard,

00:12:57.770 --> 00:13:00.440
unstretched distance,
and then you stretch it or

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:03.620
compress it and the energy goes
up, like a parabola.

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:10.440
Now the slope of that parabola
tells you what?

00:13:10.440 --> 00:13:10.960
Student:  The force.
 

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:11.879
Prof: The force.
 

00:13:11.879 --> 00:13:12.428
That's what's linear.
 

00:13:12.428 --> 00:13:17.009
As we stretch it further and
further, the slope gets bigger.

00:13:17.009 --> 00:13:20.678
The force is proportional to
the displacement.

00:13:20.678 --> 00:13:24.932
Okay, now there could be other
kinds of force laws,

00:13:24.932 --> 00:13:28.928
like electrical charges,
Coulomb, or gravity.

00:13:28.928 --> 00:13:35.332
So that's a different force
law, inverse square force law,

00:13:35.332 --> 00:13:39.938
and the energy then is
proportional to the

00:13:39.938 --> 00:13:43.309
displacement,
in this way.

00:13:43.309 --> 00:13:43.408
So very different.
 

