when they're very far apart.
 

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:52.139
Here it's zero when they're at
the standard distance.

00:13:52.139 --> 00:13:55.914
And so as you bring oppositely
charged particles together,

00:13:55.914 --> 00:13:59.226
the energy goes down
infinitely, as they get really

00:13:59.226 --> 00:13:59.889
close.
 

00:13:59.889 --> 00:14:04.977
Okay, and now if we look at the
force here, as we go out the

00:14:04.977 --> 00:14:08.860
force gets smaller,
the slope gets smaller.

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:12.162
Now suppose you had a particle
that was connected to a spring

00:14:12.162 --> 00:14:14.364
on each side,
as in this chain that we're

00:14:14.364 --> 00:14:15.190
stretching.
 

00:14:15.190 --> 00:14:19.803
And just to be general I made
the second string -- oh I say

00:14:19.803 --> 00:14:24.283
stronger, it's in fact weaker;
it doesn't go up as rapidly --

00:14:24.283 --> 00:14:25.960
I'll have to change that.
 

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:30.850
Okay now, but at some point the
slopes of the red and the blue,

00:14:30.850 --> 00:14:33.293
at some distance,
some position,

00:14:33.293 --> 00:14:35.740
will be equal and opposite.
 

00:14:35.740 --> 00:14:37.908
There.
 

00:14:37.908 --> 00:14:41.360
Okay, what's the force on the
central particle at that point?

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:42.440
Students:  Zero.
 

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:43.210
Prof: Zero.
 

00:14:43.210 --> 00:14:44.210
They balance.
 

00:14:44.210 --> 00:14:49.857
So if we added those two
energies together to get the sum

00:14:49.857 --> 00:14:55.809
of the two, on this central
particle, it looks like that.

00:14:55.809 --> 00:14:58.360
So there's a balanced minimum.
 

00:14:58.360 --> 00:15:02.222
There's a well defined position
where the particle in the center

00:15:02.222 --> 00:15:05.471
of this chain will just sit
there and it'll be hard to

00:15:05.471 --> 00:15:06.269
displace.
 

00:15:06.269 --> 00:15:07.759
So it can vibrate.
 

00:15:07.759 --> 00:15:09.629
Okay?
 

00:15:09.629 --> 00:15:11.070
Now how about in the other case?
 

00:15:11.070 --> 00:15:14.407
How about if it were electrical
charges or gravity or something

00:15:14.407 --> 00:15:17.960
like that, an inverse square law
that's holding things together?

00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:20.306
Then the second one is going to
look like that,

00:15:20.306 --> 00:15:22.038
and that one is indeed
stronger.

00:15:22.038 --> 00:15:25.619
So they're two flanking bodies
and we're interested in the

00:15:25.619 --> 00:15:27.879
position of the one in the
middle.

00:15:27.879 --> 00:15:31.567
And again, there'll be some
point where they balance,

00:15:31.567 --> 00:15:34.051
right there,
where they're equal and

00:15:34.051 --> 00:15:35.470
opposite slopes.
 

00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:37.370
How will this differ from the
first case?

00:15:37.370 --> 00:15:42.803
Can you see what's going to
happen when we add these two

00:15:42.803 --> 00:15:43.889
together?
 

00:15:43.889 --> 00:15:46.399
Is it going to look more or
less like the one on the left?

00:15:46.399 --> 00:15:47.798
Student: 
&gt;

00:15:47.798 --> 00:15:51.370
Prof: It's going to look
like that.

00:15:51.370 --> 00:15:55.440
And now there is no balanced
minimum in the middle.

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:59.711
There's not a position where
the thing will just sit there,

00:15:59.711 --> 00:16:02.804
because it's always more
strongly affected,

00:16:02.804 --> 00:16:06.120
and attracted,
by the one it's closer to.

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:09.631
There's some place where
there's zero force but it's not

00:16:09.631 --> 00:16:10.908
a stable position.
 

00:16:10.908 --> 00:16:15.288
Because if it displaces ever so
slightly, it'll keep on going.

00:16:15.288 --> 00:16:19.303
So that one is a -- for the two
of them -- is a single minimum,

00:16:19.303 --> 00:16:21.570
and this one is a double
minimum.

00:16:21.570 --> 00:16:26.980
And for the people who came
early, there was a contest that

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:30.620
if you won it,
you could get an A in the

00:16:30.620 --> 00:16:33.980
course, and the contest is this.
 

00:16:33.980 --> 00:16:46.659
Here's a magnet, hanging here.
 

00:16:46.659 --> 00:16:55.529
And I'll stop it.
 

00:16:55.529 --> 00:17:00.075
Okay, and here are two magnets,
the ones that will flank that

00:17:00.075 --> 00:17:00.528
one.
 

00:17:00.528 --> 00:17:04.838
And if I get it just right,
it'll just sit there,

00:17:04.838 --> 00:17:08.788
the attraction to the two will
balance it.

00:17:08.788 --> 00:17:22.108
So I'll put it on here,
and try to get my A.

00:17:22.108 --> 00:17:28.289
So I'll get the string where it
would balance right there.

00:17:28.289 --> 00:17:44.910
Ah.
 

00:17:44.910 --> 00:17:45.769
Okay?
 

00:17:45.769 --> 00:17:47.890
There is no stable position.
 

00:17:47.890 --> 00:17:50.910
Nobody got their A that way.
 

00:17:50.910 --> 00:17:51.538
Right?
 

00:17:51.538 --> 00:17:57.375
Because it's an inverse law,
so it's always more strongly

00:17:57.375 --> 00:18:00.710
attracted to the closer thing.
 

00:18:00.710 --> 00:18:05.768
So you can't win with that,
you can't get a balanced

00:18:05.768 --> 00:18:06.858
position.
 

00:18:06.858 --> 00:18:10.210
Now I'm going to get these off
here.

00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:28.240
And back to the show.
 

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:32.053
So with springs you might be
able to make a stable polyatomic

00:18:32.053 --> 00:18:36.135
molecule from point atoms --
we saw a spring model before in

00:18:36.135 --> 00:18:40.845
the last lecture --
but you can't do it with ions

00:18:40.845 --> 00:18:44.720
and you can't do it with
magnets.

00:18:44.720 --> 00:18:48.826
However, Hooke's law can't do
it -- it can't be springs,

00:18:48.826 --> 00:18:51.440
because Hooke's law never
breaks.

00:18:51.440 --> 00:18:54.880
So we need a different kind of
force law.

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:58.981
Does anybody know a force law
-- what it looks like -- the

00:18:58.981 --> 00:19:03.372
form of the force between atoms
or the energy for stretching a

00:19:03.372 --> 00:19:04.019
bond?
 

00:19:04.019 --> 00:19:05.660
You ever seen a picture of such
a thing?

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:07.490
Student: 
&gt;

00:19:07.490 --> 00:19:09.471
Prof: It's called the
Morse potential,

00:19:09.471 --> 00:19:12.130
or one form of it at least is
called the Morse potential.

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:14.993
And it's not something
fundamental, it's not a law of

00:19:14.993 --> 00:19:15.490
nature.
 

00:19:15.490 --> 00:19:18.770
It was thought up by a
physicist at Princeton in 1929,

00:19:18.770 --> 00:19:21.308
because it's mathematically
convenient;

00:19:21.308 --> 00:19:24.961
so you could solve quantum
mechanical problems if you used

00:19:24.961 --> 00:19:26.180
Morse potentials.
 

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:27.930
And the idea is this.
 

00:19:27.930 --> 00:19:31.166
You have two neighbors and you
look at the position of the one

00:19:31.166 --> 00:19:34.192
on the right and it could be
there and the energy would be

00:19:34.192 --> 00:19:36.940
minimum;
that's the bond distance, right?

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:39.430
And if you move it further to
the right, the energy goes up;

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:41.640
move it to the left,
the energy goes up.

00:19:41.640 --> 00:19:43.941
Okay, that's the Morse
potential, and we're just

00:19:43.941 --> 00:19:45.950
holding the neighbor on the left
fixed.

00:19:45.950 --> 00:19:49.194
Now we could put another
neighbor on the other side and

00:19:49.194 --> 00:19:51.480
have another curve of the same
sort;

00:19:51.480 --> 00:19:54.288
stretching the second bond.
 

00:19:54.288 --> 00:19:57.864
Or we could have it be a chain
and have both neighbors there,

00:19:57.864 --> 00:20:01.380
and the sum of those two now
has a minimum in the middle.

00:20:01.380 --> 00:20:04.420
It's a single minimum,
like we got with Hooke's law.

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:08.440
So that means that atom in the
middle would just stay there.

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:12.247
And now we're going to grab
those sticks on either side and

00:20:12.247 --> 00:20:14.019
pull the neighbors apart.
 

00:20:14.019 --> 00:20:18.680
So if we pull them apart,
it's still a single minimum.

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:22.131
And if we pull them apart
further, it's still a single

00:20:22.131 --> 00:20:24.410
minimum, although it's very
flat.

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:28.943
And if we pull it further,
it pops and it becomes a double

00:20:28.943 --> 00:20:29.740
minimum.
 

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:33.390
And if we keep going the double
minimum gets more pronounced.

00:20:33.390 --> 00:20:35.920
Now here's an interesting
question.

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:39.996
At what point -- how far do you
have to stretch it before it

00:20:39.996 --> 00:20:40.480
pops?
 

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:43.400
That's the question we were
asking, right?

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:49.424
How can you look at those
curves and tell how far apart

00:20:49.424 --> 00:20:54.670
you have to stretch it before
the chain pops?

00:20:54.670 --> 00:20:55.348
Shai?
 

00:20:55.348 --> 00:20:57.880
Student:  The bottom is
flat.

00:20:57.880 --> 00:21:02.384
So when the curve and the plot
was flat, then that's as far as

00:21:02.384 --> 00:21:05.811
it could go because --
Prof: What do you mean

00:21:05.811 --> 00:21:06.140
flat?
 

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:08.509
There's a name for a thing like
that in graphs.

00:21:08.509 --> 00:21:09.528
Student:  Inflection.
 

00:21:09.528 --> 00:21:10.980
Prof: It's the
inflection point.

00:21:10.980 --> 00:21:15.829
It's when the curvature changes
from being this way,

00:21:15.829 --> 00:21:19.157
like Hooke's law,
to being this way,

00:21:19.157 --> 00:21:20.108
right?
 

00:21:20.108 --> 00:21:24.308
So when the inflection points
cross, then the chain pops.

00:21:24.308 --> 00:21:27.273
Okay, so force laws are going
to make a lot of difference in

00:21:27.273 --> 00:21:30.059
how atoms behave,
and if really knew the force

00:21:30.059 --> 00:21:33.940
law we'd be in a great position
for understanding chemistry.

00:21:33.940 --> 00:21:38.662
It snaps at the inflection
point where it changes from a

00:21:38.662 --> 00:21:43.470
direct to an inverse dependence
on distance for force.

00:21:43.470 --> 00:21:45.460
Okay, but what
are bonds?

00:21:45.460 --> 00:21:46.997
Newton said,
"We'll look for the

00:21:46.997 --> 00:21:47.509
law."
 

00:21:47.509 --> 00:21:49.818
And it's sort of,
the law is sort of like Morse,

00:21:49.818 --> 00:21:51.118
but we don't know where it came
from,

00:21:51.118 --> 00:21:52.779
because we don't know how it
works,

00:21:52.779 --> 00:21:54.338
we don't know what it really is.
 

00:21:54.338 --> 00:21:57.009
So can we find out what it
really is?

00:21:57.009 --> 00:22:02.970
Well in the nineteenth century
they discovered bonds.

00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:06.150
And this is a picture from
1861, we'll talk about this

00:22:06.150 --> 00:22:06.630
later.
 

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:10.675
It's one of the first
depictions that's recognizable

00:22:10.675 --> 00:22:13.930
by people today of bonds between
atoms.

00:22:13.930 --> 00:22:17.413
So there are different numbers
of these lines,

00:22:17.413 --> 00:22:19.890
valences, for different atoms.
 

00:22:19.890 --> 00:22:22.981
Hydrogen has one;
carbon has four;

00:22:22.981 --> 00:22:25.700
oxygen two; nitrogen three.
 

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:27.140
Why do the elements differ?
 

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:30.980
Why don't they all have the
same valence?

00:22:30.980 --> 00:22:36.102
And even more complicated,
sometimes nitrogen is three and

00:22:36.102 --> 00:22:38.078
sometimes it's five.
 

00:22:38.078 --> 00:22:41.407
For example,
you have NH_3_ but

00:22:41.407 --> 00:22:45.403
you also have NH_4Cl,
where there are five things

00:22:45.403 --> 00:22:48.150
associated with the nitrogen.
 

00:22:48.150 --> 00:22:50.160
So how do you understand the
valence?

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:52.150
That was the challenge for
people.

00:22:52.150 --> 00:22:56.548
They had figured out that there
was valence, but why?

00:22:56.548 --> 00:23:00.519
How could you predict the
valence of a new element?

00:23:00.519 --> 00:23:05.969
Well Gertrude and Robert
Robinson published a paper in

00:23:05.969 --> 00:23:11.109
1917 which showed this picture
of ammonia, NH_3.

00:23:11.109 --> 00:23:13.289
What's the loop?
 

00:23:13.289 --> 00:23:14.618
Pardon me?
 

00:23:14.618 --> 00:23:16.960
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:23:16.960 --> 00:23:19.462
Prof: Someone said --
hold your hand up so that people

00:23:19.462 --> 00:23:20.089
can hear you.
 

00:23:20.089 --> 00:23:20.910
Okay yes.
 

00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:22.259
Student:  A lone pair on
nitrogen.

00:23:22.259 --> 00:23:26.710
Prof: A lone pair on
nitrogen -- wrong.

00:23:26.710 --> 00:23:31.163
It looks like the lone pair on
nitrogen but the lone pair

00:23:31.163 --> 00:23:33.548
didn't come along that soon.
 

00:23:33.548 --> 00:23:36.681
What the loop means,
if you look at it in the

00:23:36.681 --> 00:23:40.240
context, is what makes NH_3_
reactive?

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:43.067
In this term,
this is what they wrote:

00:23:43.067 --> 00:23:46.886
"It may reasonably be
assumed that the partial

00:23:46.886 --> 00:23:51.319
dissociation is a stage in the
complete process."

00:23:51.319 --> 00:23:52.818
So the bonds begin to break.
 

00:23:52.818 --> 00:23:57.565
This loop begins to break to
become a weaker loop and two

00:23:57.565 --> 00:24:01.038
other partial valences,
in this theory.

00:24:01.038 --> 00:24:05.821
And those valences begin to
associate with partial valences

00:24:05.821 --> 00:24:06.730
from HCl.
 

00:24:06.730 --> 00:24:09.930
Right?
 

00:24:09.930 --> 00:24:12.461
The loop is a
"latent"

00:24:12.461 --> 00:24:13.279
valence.
 

00:24:13.279 --> 00:24:15.640
You know what 'latent' means?
 

00:24:15.640 --> 00:24:19.910
Latent is the opposite of
patent.

00:24:19.910 --> 00:24:24.470
Latent means hidden;
patent is revealed.

00:24:24.470 --> 00:24:27.355
When you get a patent on
something it means that you tell

00:24:27.355 --> 00:24:30.445
everybody how to do it but the
government protects your right

00:24:30.445 --> 00:24:32.609
to do it for a certain period of
time.

00:24:32.609 --> 00:24:34.990
Latent means it's hidden.
 

00:24:34.990 --> 00:24:37.805
So there's a hidden valence,
these loops,

00:24:37.805 --> 00:24:40.548
but they can become available,
right?

00:24:40.548 --> 00:24:43.202
It must be assumed in some
cases, as for example the

00:24:43.202 --> 00:24:45.700
combination of ammonia with
hydrochloric acid.

00:24:45.700 --> 00:24:49.329
Now, so you can get a reaction
and get the product,

00:24:49.329 --> 00:24:52.670
which has all five valences of
nitrogen now.

00:24:52.670 --> 00:24:57.180
But how do you know there's not
another loop on nitrogen,

00:24:57.180 --> 00:25:01.207
that you could break open and
make it seven valent,

00:25:01.207 --> 00:25:03.058
or nine, or eleven?
 

00:25:03.058 --> 00:25:07.990
Or maybe you could break a loop
into three.

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:11.843
So might latent valence loop
explain the trivalence and

00:25:11.843 --> 00:25:15.838
pentavalence of nitrogen,
or the amine-HCl reactivity?

00:25:15.838 --> 00:25:18.109
The trouble is it's too
slippery a concept.

00:25:18.109 --> 00:25:19.509
It explains everything.
 

00:25:19.509 --> 00:25:21.019
You could explain anything you
wanted to.

00:25:21.019 --> 00:25:23.950
You could explain eighty-four
valence of nitrogen or

00:25:23.950 --> 00:25:24.640
something.
 

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:26.673
Anything that comes along,
you'd say, "Ah ha,

00:25:26.673 --> 00:25:28.500
there are that many latent
valences."

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:30.509
But how do you know there are
not more?

00:25:30.509 --> 00:25:33.359
Why do you have latent valences?
 

00:25:33.359 --> 00:25:35.858
When do you have them?
 

00:25:35.858 --> 00:25:38.548
When and why do you have
partial dissociation?

00:25:38.548 --> 00:25:43.132
This thing didn't explain
anything, or explained

00:25:43.132 --> 00:25:44.400
everything.
 

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:52.253
Now, at this point I want you
to smile so I can learn who you

00:25:52.253 --> 00:25:53.038
are.
 

00:25:53.038 --> 00:27:13.510
&lt;&lt;Professor McBride takes
pictures of the class

00:27:13.510 --> 00:27:39.818
members&gt;&gt;
 

00:27:39.818 --> 00:27:44.970
Prof: So the electron
was discovered in 1897.

00:27:44.970 --> 00:27:46.808
So maybe that has something to
do with it.

00:27:46.808 --> 00:27:50.643
And the guy who had associated
electrons with valence was

00:27:50.643 --> 00:27:51.670
G.N. Lewis.
 

00:27:51.670 --> 00:27:59.430
And this is a picture of him as
a Harvard undergraduate in 1894.

00:27:59.430 --> 00:28:03.001
And this is eight years later,
when he was an instructor at

00:28:03.001 --> 00:28:05.115
Harvard,
and he then went to establish

00:28:05.115 --> 00:28:07.984
the Chemistry Department at the
University of California at

00:28:07.984 --> 00:28:08.529
Berkley.
 

00:28:08.529 --> 00:28:09.220
Student:  Yay!
 

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:13.460
&gt;
 

00:28:13.460 --> 00:28:17.940
Prof: But when he was at
Harvard in 1902 he used these

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:21.115
lecture notes,
and what he was trying to

00:28:21.115 --> 00:28:25.115
explain was the periodic table,
why you go across in eight and

00:28:25.115 --> 00:28:27.048
then another eight and another
eight,

00:28:27.048 --> 00:28:32.541
and so on, and why you have
electron transfers from some

00:28:32.541 --> 00:28:34.838
atoms to other atoms.
 

00:28:34.838 --> 00:28:40.301
And he said if the electrons in
an atom are arranged at the

00:28:40.301 --> 00:28:43.728
corners of a cube,
then you -- eight is this very

00:28:43.728 --> 00:28:46.614
special number,
because that occupies all the

00:28:46.614 --> 00:28:48.108
corners of the cube.
 

00:28:48.108 --> 00:28:50.318
So if there's a desire,
for some reason,

00:28:50.318 --> 00:28:53.608
to complete octets,
then you can explain

00:28:53.608 --> 00:28:58.332
periodicity and see why some
atoms give up an electron to

00:28:58.332 --> 00:29:03.477
lose the outer shell and others
gain one to complete the outer

00:29:03.477 --> 00:29:04.490
shell.
 

00:29:04.490 --> 00:29:09.251
Okay, so but it also could
explain how you get bonding,

00:29:09.251 --> 00:29:13.789
if you like to have octets;
not just electron transfer but

00:29:13.789 --> 00:29:15.970
the formation of covalent bonds.
 

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:18.440
So, for example,
here's two chlorines.

00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:22.460
Each has only seven;
the octet isn't complete.

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:26.999
But if you bring them together
and they share an edge,

00:29:26.999 --> 00:29:29.740
then both octets are complete.
 

00:29:29.740 --> 00:29:32.411
He doesn't say
why octets should

00:29:32.411 --> 00:29:35.736
be so great, but if they're
octets then you could explain

00:29:35.736 --> 00:29:36.329
bonds.
 

00:29:36.329 --> 00:29:39.019
How about double bonds?
 

00:29:39.019 --> 00:29:42.740
Suppose you had two oxygen
atoms.

00:29:42.740 --> 00:29:43.569
What do you do now?
 

00:29:43.569 --> 00:29:44.839
Anybody see?
 

00:29:44.839 --> 00:29:45.710
What?
 

00:29:45.710 --> 00:29:46.858
Student:  Put the faces
together.

00:29:46.858 --> 00:29:51.031
Prof: Put faces
together, share two edges,

00:29:51.031 --> 00:29:53.640
and then both have an octet.
 

00:29:53.640 --> 00:29:57.580
Now, suppose you want to put
nitrogens together and form a

00:29:57.580 --> 00:29:58.549
triple bond.
 

00:29:58.549 --> 00:30:00.349
Now how do you do it?
 

00:30:00.349 --> 00:30:02.910
Student:  Squish it.
 

00:30:02.910 --> 00:30:07.259
Prof: Push it hard,
force it like a picture puzzle?

00:30:07.259 --> 00:30:07.910
Student:  Yes.
 

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:08.509
Prof: Put it in there.
 

00:30:08.509 --> 00:30:09.789
Student: You need to
push it.

00:30:09.789 --> 00:30:11.950
Student:  You did it.
 

00:30:11.950 --> 00:30:15.390
Prof: It won't do it.
 

00:30:15.390 --> 00:30:19.990
But about ten years later he
figured out how to do it.

00:30:19.990 --> 00:30:25.048
What you do is take the
electrons -- nitrogen has 5 --

00:30:25.048 --> 00:30:30.776
but instead of using an octet,
you contract it along opposing

00:30:30.776 --> 00:30:32.588
edges this way.
 

00:30:32.588 --> 00:30:35.598
So what was an octet,
what was a cube,

00:30:35.598 --> 00:30:36.819
becomes what?
 

00:30:36.819 --> 00:30:38.140
Student:  A tetrahedron.
 

00:30:38.140 --> 00:30:41.308
Prof: A tetrahedron.
 

00:30:41.308 --> 00:30:46.031
And now if you take two
tetrahedra, you can put a face

00:30:46.031 --> 00:30:49.240
together and complete both
octets.

00:30:49.240 --> 00:30:52.200
But this wasn't such a great
development.

00:30:52.200 --> 00:30:54.374
He did this,
published this,

00:30:54.374 --> 00:30:55.180
in 1916.
 

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:58.593
But the tetrahedral
distribution of the bonds in

00:30:58.593 --> 00:31:03.022
carbon had been known by organic
chemists for 40 years by that

00:31:03.022 --> 00:31:07.021
time,
that the tetrahedron was a very

00:31:07.021 --> 00:31:09.240
important structure.
 

00:31:09.240 --> 00:31:14.286
So a good theory should be
realistic and it should be

00:31:14.286 --> 00:31:15.160
simple.
 

00:31:15.160 --> 00:31:18.048
But there's a tension between
these things.

00:31:18.048 --> 00:31:22.761
It should at least be as simple
as possible, but that may not be

00:31:22.761 --> 00:31:26.088
very simple;
that's why it takes us five

00:31:26.088 --> 00:31:26.680
weeks.
 

00:31:26.680 --> 00:31:29.959
In regard to the facts it
should allow a number of

00:31:29.959 --> 00:31:30.829
properties.
 

00:31:30.829 --> 00:31:32.568
It should allow prediction.
 

00:31:32.568 --> 00:31:35.670
You should be able to say how
will these atoms react;

00:31:35.670 --> 00:31:39.423
how will this molecule react;
what valence should nitrogen

00:31:39.423 --> 00:31:43.165
have;
how can it be both pentavalent

00:31:43.165 --> 00:31:44.880
and trivalent?
 

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:48.006
A little below this on the
scale of desirability is

00:31:48.006 --> 00:31:48.818
suggestion.
 

00:31:48.818 --> 00:31:52.355
A theory may -- even if it
doesn't give you the proper

00:31:52.355 --> 00:31:56.558
thing, may at least suggest some
experiment that would be really

00:31:56.558 --> 00:31:57.558
good to do.
 

00:31:57.558 --> 00:32:03.422
Below that is explanation --
according to my theory all these

00:32:03.422 --> 00:32:08.501
known facts fit together,
but who knows about any new

00:32:08.501 --> 00:32:09.480
thing.
 

00:32:09.480 --> 00:32:13.240
And lowest is classification
and remembering;

00:32:13.240 --> 00:32:16.736
like Roy G. Biv allows you to
remember the colors of the

00:32:16.736 --> 00:32:20.358
spectrum, but there's nothing
fundamental about that.

00:32:20.358 --> 00:32:24.093
So even if you have a crummy
thing it might allow you to at

00:32:24.093 --> 00:32:27.440
least remember some facts and
organize them maybe.

00:32:27.440 --> 00:32:30.827
Okay, but those last two are
not prediction,

00:32:30.827 --> 00:32:34.211
they're post-diction;
you only use it to explain

00:32:34.211 --> 00:32:37.838
things that are already known as
a way of remembering them.

00:32:37.838 --> 00:32:41.955
So from the number of valence
electrons we'd like to predict

00:32:41.955 --> 00:32:45.722
how many atoms of different
types come together to form

00:32:45.722 --> 00:32:46.700
molecules.
 

00:32:46.700 --> 00:32:51.420
That's constitution -- the
nature and the sequence of bonds

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:53.130
-- and the valence.
 

00:32:53.130 --> 00:32:55.661
We'd like to know the structure
of molecules,

00:32:55.661 --> 00:32:57.788
the distance between atoms,
angles.

00:32:57.788 --> 00:33:00.798
We'd like to know how charge is
distributed within molecules.

00:33:00.798 --> 00:33:03.608
Are some regions positive and
others negative?

00:33:03.608 --> 00:33:05.630
We'd like to know what the
energy of the molecule is.

00:33:05.630 --> 00:33:08.957
Is this arrangement of the
atoms better or worse than an

00:33:08.957 --> 00:33:10.528
alternative arrangement?
 

00:33:10.528 --> 00:33:14.720
And we'd like to know about
reactivity.

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:18.423
So Lewis explains constitution,
the nature and the sequence of

00:33:18.423 --> 00:33:18.910
bonds.
 

00:33:18.910 --> 00:33:20.170
"Nature"
means like single,

00:33:20.170 --> 00:33:23.512
double, triple,
and "sequence"

00:33:23.512 --> 00:33:27.200
means which atoms are connected
to which.

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:32.894
So he has electrons,
valence, and also he added

00:33:32.894 --> 00:33:35.000
unshared pairs.
 

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.779
So you count up how many,
from the atomic weight or the

00:33:37.779 --> 00:33:40.558
atomic number or the position in
the periodic table.

00:33:40.558 --> 00:33:44.044
You get how many valence
electrons, how many of these

00:33:44.044 --> 00:33:45.720
outer octets are there.
 

00:33:45.720 --> 00:33:49.633
And then you can figure that
the valence of hydrogen should

00:33:49.633 --> 00:33:51.792
be one, boron three,
carbon four,

00:33:51.792 --> 00:33:54.559
but then down again,
three, two, one.

00:33:54.559 --> 00:33:58.420
So here's ammonia, NH_3.
 

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:00.410
It works fine and it has an
unshared pair.

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:04.640
But why do you have octets?
 

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:07.440
Why not sextets?
 

00:34:07.440 --> 00:34:13.389
And why do you have a pair for
hydrogen?

00:34:13.389 --> 00:34:18.570
Why not an octet for hydrogen
also?

00:34:18.570 --> 00:34:21.980
Okay, so let's just apply it to
HCN.

00:34:21.980 --> 00:34:25.905
So if carbon has four,
that makes possible a single

00:34:25.905 --> 00:34:29.360
bond to hydrogen,
a triple bond to carbon.

00:34:29.360 --> 00:34:32.989
Everybody has their octet
except hydrogen that only wants

00:34:32.989 --> 00:34:33.380
two.
 

00:34:33.380 --> 00:34:34.630
So everybody's happy.
 

00:34:34.630 --> 00:34:38.050
And we can abbreviate it this
way, and leave the dot.

00:34:38.050 --> 00:34:40.556
Lewis actually thought of
drawing a colon,

00:34:40.556 --> 00:34:43.309
a pair of dots,
to denote an unshared pair.

00:34:43.309 --> 00:34:45.530
So that's his notation.
 

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:47.730
So NH_3.
 

00:34:47.730 --> 00:34:49.030
Bingo!
 

00:34:49.030 --> 00:34:51.460
How about BH_3?
 

00:34:51.460 --> 00:34:53.059
Just fine.
 

00:34:53.059 --> 00:34:54.980
But here's something new.
 

00:34:54.980 --> 00:34:57.277
The organic chemists would
already have known this,

00:34:57.277 --> 00:34:58.750
they knew the valence numbers.
 

00:34:58.750 --> 00:35:01.876
The electrons just added
something to it but didn't say

00:35:01.876 --> 00:35:03.150
anything really new.
 

00:35:03.150 --> 00:35:09.166
But here's something new,
that BH_3_ reacts

00:35:09.166 --> 00:35:12.869
with NH_3, to give a new bond.
 

00:35:12.869 --> 00:35:16.570
Now here's a puzzle.
 

00:35:16.570 --> 00:35:23.380
It's also true that BH_3 reacts
with BH_3_.

00:35:23.380 --> 00:35:29.570
That doesn't look like
Lewis.

00:35:29.570 --> 00:35:33.907
And the bond is reasonably
strong, it's half as strong as a

00:35:33.907 --> 00:35:35.480
carbon-carbon bond.
 

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:39.219
So what's the glue that holds
B_2H_6 together?

00:35:39.219 --> 00:35:44.699
And we'll come back to that
fourteen lectures from now.

00:35:44.699 --> 00:35:45.579
But there's another thing.
 

00:35:45.579 --> 00:35:49.492
There's bookkeeping that you do
with Lewis structures to assign

00:35:49.492 --> 00:35:52.543
what's called formal charges;
not real charges,

00:35:52.543 --> 00:35:56.402
just what charges you write in
the formula, and you hope they

00:35:56.402 --> 00:35:57.559
mean something.
 

00:35:57.559 --> 00:36:01.213
And the bookkeeping scheme you
use is that each atom is

00:36:01.213 --> 00:36:04.260
assigned half interest in the
bonding pair.

00:36:04.260 --> 00:36:07.706
So if there's a bonding pair,
for bookkeeping purposes you

00:36:07.706 --> 00:36:09.518
assign one electron to each.
 

00:36:09.518 --> 00:36:13.474
It may be they aren't evenly
shared, but the bookkeepers

00:36:13.474 --> 00:36:14.409
don't care.
 

00:36:14.409 --> 00:36:16.514
Incidentally,
speaking of bookkeepers not

00:36:16.514 --> 00:36:19.365
caring,
there's -- people have had a

00:36:19.365 --> 00:36:23.518
lot of nonsense trying to get
signed up for lab,

00:36:23.518 --> 00:36:28.288
because the people who run the
system don't allow teachers to

00:36:28.288 --> 00:36:32.739
have access to the thing to see
the problems you face.

00:36:32.739 --> 00:36:35.340
So I have no way of telling --
I can't get on to your system.

00:36:35.340 --> 00:36:37.849
Has everybody figured out how
to sign up for lab by now?

00:36:37.849 --> 00:36:38.869
Student:  Yes.
 

00:36:38.869 --> 00:36:40.380
Prof: If anybody still
has problems,

00:36:40.380 --> 00:36:43.416
after class Dr. DiMeglio can
take you to the computer center

00:36:43.416 --> 00:36:44.550
here and help you.
 

00:36:44.550 --> 00:36:47.969
So next year presumably it'll
be easier.

00:36:47.969 --> 00:36:49.840
This is a new system this year.
 

00:36:49.840 --> 00:36:54.230
But anyhow, back to the
bookkeepers here.

00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:57.639
So these formal charges are not
necessarily real charges,

00:36:57.639 --> 00:37:01.110
they're just what you write
when you draw the formulas.

00:37:01.110 --> 00:37:06.047
Okay, so we split the BN
electrons between the B and the

00:37:06.047 --> 00:37:10.090
N, and we split the hydrogen
bonds as well.

00:37:10.090 --> 00:37:16.494
So nitrogen now has those four
electrons, where it brought five

00:37:16.494 --> 00:37:19.179
to the table originally.
 

00:37:19.179 --> 00:37:22.079
So it has a positive charge.
 

00:37:22.079 --> 00:37:26.079
Tetravalent nitrogen is
positive in the Lewis structure.

00:37:26.079 --> 00:37:27.320
Why?
 

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:31.425
Because in forming a fourth
bond, it gave up half-interest

00:37:31.425 --> 00:37:35.530
in one of its electron ,
the ones in the unshared pair.

00:37:35.530 --> 00:37:37.922
So it lost a charge,
a negative charge,

00:37:37.922 --> 00:37:39.369
and becomes positive.
 

00:37:39.369 --> 00:37:41.987
By the same token,
what else can you write in this

00:37:41.987 --> 00:37:42.630
structure?
 

00:37:42.630 --> 00:37:45.030
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:37:45.030 --> 00:37:45.969
Student:  It's negative.
 

00:37:45.969 --> 00:37:49.431
Prof: A negative charge
on boron, because it got

00:37:49.431 --> 00:37:51.099
half-interest in a pair.
 

00:37:51.099 --> 00:37:54.320
But that's just bookkeeping.
 

00:37:54.320 --> 00:37:58.786
So when you write a Lewis
structure you'd write plus on

00:37:58.786 --> 00:38:01.269
nitrogen and minus on boron.
 

00:38:01.269 --> 00:38:02.929
Now is it real?
 

00:38:02.929 --> 00:38:07.324
Is there a positive charge on
nitrogen and negative charge on

00:38:07.324 --> 00:38:07.909
boron?
 

00:38:07.909 --> 00:38:12.641
Well we'll get later on to know
about what a surface potential

00:38:12.641 --> 00:38:13.030
is.
 

00:38:13.030 --> 00:38:18.121
Surface potential is the energy
a proton would have if it was on

00:38:18.121 --> 00:38:21.679
different points on the
molecular surface.

00:38:21.679 --> 00:38:29.353
For this purpose you have to
define what the surface is of

00:38:29.353 --> 00:38:30.429
BNH_6.
 

00:38:30.429 --> 00:38:33.215
There's a way of doing that;
we won't talk about it now,

00:38:33.215 --> 00:38:34.590
that's jumping the gun.
 

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:39.018
But that's the surface,
and it's color coded to show

00:38:39.018 --> 00:38:44.056
the energy a proton would have
if it were on the surface at

00:38:44.056 --> 00:38:45.360
that point.
 

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:49.472
So what you see is that the
energy of the proton would be

00:38:49.472 --> 00:38:52.630
high, if it's here,
where it's very blue.

00:38:52.630 --> 00:38:58.251
The energy of the proton would
be low if it's in this region

00:38:58.251 --> 00:38:58.920
here.
 

00:38:58.920 --> 00:39:01.659
Is that consistent with what we
were talking about?

00:39:01.659 --> 00:39:02.619
Student:  Yes.
 

00:39:02.619 --> 00:39:06.730
Prof: Where would a
proton be low in energy?

00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:10.277
Where there's negative charge,
and it would be high in energy

00:39:10.277 --> 00:39:12.170
when there is positive charge.
 

00:39:12.170 --> 00:39:15.789
So this molecule,
according to quantum mechanics,

00:39:15.789 --> 00:39:19.710
is positive on the left and
negative on the right.

00:39:19.710 --> 00:39:23.077
And that's exactly what we
have, it's consistent with what

00:39:23.077 --> 00:39:23.670
we have.
 

00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:27.699
And now Lewis also explains
where pentavalent nitrogen comes

00:39:27.699 --> 00:39:30.980
from, because there's an ionic
bond there too.

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:32.760
Tetravalent nitrogen is plus.
 

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:37.257
So there's just a Coulombic
attraction between ammonium and

00:39:37.257 --> 00:39:38.110
chloride.
 

00:39:38.110 --> 00:39:39.610
So that's a great contribution.
 

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:42.338
Now there are other things you
can understand in terms of Lewis

00:39:42.338 --> 00:39:42.909
structures.
 

00:39:42.909 --> 00:39:46.952
Like you have an amine and it
can react with an oxygen to give

00:39:46.952 --> 00:39:49.934
an amine oxide,
which is positive on nitrogen,

00:39:49.934 --> 00:39:51.460
negative on oxygen.
 

00:39:51.460 --> 00:39:56.199
Or you can have a sulfide,
which can react with an oxygen,

00:39:56.199 --> 00:39:58.030
to give a sulfoxide.
 

00:39:58.030 --> 00:40:02.121
Or what else can happen,
with a sulfur,

00:40:02.121 --> 00:40:05.460
what additionally can happen?
 

00:40:05.460 --> 00:40:06.159
Student:  Another oxygen.
 

00:40:06.159 --> 00:40:09.126
Prof: It could do
another oxygen,

00:40:09.126 --> 00:40:11.940
and give a sulfone,
as it's called.

00:40:11.940 --> 00:40:15.110
So Lewis explains this.
 

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:19.159
So there are problems to drill
on Lewis structures.

00:40:19.159 --> 00:40:21.679
They're on the Web,
go look at them.

00:40:21.679 --> 00:40:26.130
One of them is draw Lewis dot
structures for HNC,

00:40:26.130 --> 00:40:29.840
in that order,
H then N -- we did HCN;

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:33.389
but do HNC.
 

00:40:33.389 --> 00:40:38.369
And then try HCNO with CNO in
all six linear orders;

00:40:38.369 --> 00:40:41.438
that is, nitrogen in the
middle, carbon in the middle,

00:40:41.438 --> 00:40:44.215
oxygen in the middle,
and then hydrogen on either

00:40:44.215 --> 00:40:44.679
end.
 

00:40:44.679 --> 00:40:47.570
And it's also possible to make
a ring of CNO and put the

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:49.409
hydrogen on any of the
positions.

00:40:49.409 --> 00:40:54.010
So just practice drawing Lewis
structures of those.

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:56.559
And start memorizing functional
groups.

00:40:56.559 --> 00:40:59.155
We do precious little
memorizing in this course,

00:40:59.155 --> 00:41:01.639
compared to most organic
chemistry courses.

00:41:01.639 --> 00:41:05.137
We try to figure out how things
work so that you can predict

00:41:05.137 --> 00:41:06.559
without memorizing it.
 

00:41:06.559 --> 00:41:08.896
But there are some things you
have to know,

00:41:08.896 --> 00:41:10.400
like the names of groups.
 

00:41:10.400 --> 00:41:12.619
Otherwise it takes forever to
talk about them.

00:41:12.619 --> 00:41:15.579
So here are the ones you have
to learn,

00:41:15.579 --> 00:41:18.764
and on the fist exam,
coming up in three weeks or

00:41:18.764 --> 00:41:21.490
whatever,
I'll give you a question where

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:25.159
you have to draw one of these
structures from the name,

00:41:25.159 --> 00:41:27.380
or give the name for a
structure.

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:29.762
These are all on the webpage;
you don't have to copy them

00:41:29.762 --> 00:41:30.000
down.
 

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:31.820
But those are simple functional
groups.

00:41:31.820 --> 00:41:33.349
&gt;
 

00:41:33.349 --> 00:41:37.340
And here are -- whoops,
oh there you go,

