There.
 

00:41:42.179 --> 00:41:44.690
They're also conjugated
functional groups.

00:41:44.690 --> 00:41:46.570
So you could run it yourself.
 

00:41:46.570 --> 00:41:51.679
Okay, now the final question
here, for today,

00:41:51.679 --> 00:41:54.630
is a thing that comes up when
you talk about Lewis structures,

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:57.639
or structures in general,
Lewis structures in particular,

00:41:57.639 --> 00:41:59.730
is equilibrium and resonance.
 

00:41:59.730 --> 00:42:02.119
How many people know what
resonance is?

00:42:02.119 --> 00:42:06.900
What is it?
 

00:42:06.900 --> 00:42:10.215
Student:  Like the same
molecule but different

00:42:10.215 --> 00:42:10.980
structure.
 

00:42:10.980 --> 00:42:12.268
Prof: Speak up a little
bit.

00:42:12.268 --> 00:42:15.043
Student:  It's the same
molecule but a different

00:42:15.043 --> 00:42:15.659
structure.
 

00:42:15.659 --> 00:42:17.550
Prof: The same molecule
but a different structure.

00:42:17.550 --> 00:42:19.300
But isn't structure a molecule?
 

00:42:19.300 --> 00:42:23.139
Student: But with that I
guess --

00:42:23.139 --> 00:42:25.436
Prof: You know like,
let me just interject a minute

00:42:25.436 --> 00:42:25.719
here.
 

00:42:25.719 --> 00:42:29.840
Like, one of the problems is
HCNO in any order.

00:42:29.840 --> 00:42:32.621
So there would be different
molecules with C in the middle,

00:42:32.621 --> 00:42:34.300
N in the middle,
O in the middle.

00:42:34.300 --> 00:42:35.550
Is that what you mean?
 

00:42:35.550 --> 00:42:36.719
Student:  No.
 

00:42:36.719 --> 00:42:39.980
I mean like it's -- if you have
a double or a triple bond,

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:43.469
it's in a different location,
it's around the central atom.

00:42:43.469 --> 00:42:47.358
Prof: Ah,
now let's -- actually resonance

00:42:47.358 --> 00:42:51.989
is one of those things where
people try to hide ignorance

00:42:51.989 --> 00:42:53.480
from ignominy.
 

00:42:53.480 --> 00:42:54.920
And let me show you what I mean
by that.

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:59.690
So here's the structure for
HCNO.

00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:02.940
And here it has all octets.
 

00:43:02.940 --> 00:43:04.449
If you go through you'll figure
that out.

00:43:04.449 --> 00:43:08.369
It has charge separation though.
 

00:43:08.369 --> 00:43:10.460
You don't like to have that in
your structures.

00:43:10.460 --> 00:43:14.030
You like not to have charges if
you can avoid it.

00:43:14.030 --> 00:43:19.230
Obviously in BNH_6 you can't
avoid it.

00:43:19.230 --> 00:43:22.324
Okay, now but you can get rid
of the charge separation by

00:43:22.324 --> 00:43:25.420
shifting that electron pair
that's on oxygen to be shared

00:43:25.420 --> 00:43:29.045
between oxygen and nitrogen;
then you don't have the charge

00:43:29.045 --> 00:43:30.219
on oxygen anymore.
 

00:43:30.219 --> 00:43:31.300
Everybody see that?
 

00:43:31.300 --> 00:43:32.469
Student:  Yeah sure.
 

00:43:32.469 --> 00:43:34.639
Prof: What's the problem
when you do that?

00:43:34.639 --> 00:43:38.570
Nitrogen now has too many
electrons.

00:43:38.570 --> 00:43:43.697
So you could shift a pair from
-- that's in the CN bond,

00:43:43.697 --> 00:43:47.800
onto the carbon,
in your drawing you make.

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:53.614
Okay, so you get this structure
shown below which has all

00:43:53.614 --> 00:43:54.550
octets.
 

00:43:54.550 --> 00:43:58.318
But there's still charge
separation, and in fact it's

00:43:58.318 --> 00:44:02.157
worse because the negative
charge, instead of being on

00:44:02.157 --> 00:44:04.260
oxygen, is now on carbon.
 

00:44:04.260 --> 00:44:07.527
So there are these two
different Lewis structures you

00:44:07.527 --> 00:44:11.237
can draw and each has its own
properties, or good things and

00:44:11.237 --> 00:44:12.179
bad things.
 

00:44:12.179 --> 00:44:17.577
Now what are the geometric
implications of there being two

00:44:17.577 --> 00:44:18.809
structures?
 

00:44:18.809 --> 00:44:22.559
It could mean that in the
middle one, in the lower one,

00:44:22.559 --> 00:44:26.240
nitrogen is exactly halfway
between carbon and oxygen,

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:28.949
because they are both double
bonds.

00:44:28.949 --> 00:44:31.929
But in the top one,
nitrogen is much closer to

00:44:31.929 --> 00:44:33.518
carbon than to oxygen.
 

00:44:33.518 --> 00:44:39.949
That could be the meaning of
this.

00:44:39.949 --> 00:44:44.510
So that if you draw a picture
of the energy,

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:48.630
as a function of the position
of the nitrogen,

00:44:48.630 --> 00:44:51.409
you could get two different
structures,

00:44:51.409 --> 00:44:54.289
one where it's further to the
left,

00:44:54.289 --> 00:44:57.190
where the nitrogen is further
to the left you have this

00:44:57.190 --> 00:44:59.675
structure,
and when the nitrogen's in the

00:44:59.675 --> 00:45:01.579
middle you have that structure.
 

00:45:01.579 --> 00:45:04.860
And you have to go up hill in
energy, it'll click;

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:07.449
as you start pushing the
nitrogen it starts,

00:45:07.449 --> 00:45:09.739
it'll click,
and it's the other one.

00:45:09.739 --> 00:45:11.289
Okay?
 

00:45:11.289 --> 00:45:15.130
That could be the way the atoms
really behave.

00:45:15.130 --> 00:45:20.268
That's called a double minimum;
we already saw a double minimum

00:45:20.268 --> 00:45:21.018
today.
 

00:45:21.018 --> 00:45:24.809
But maybe in truth it's not
this way.

00:45:24.809 --> 00:45:28.909
Maybe it's a single minimum.
 

00:45:28.909 --> 00:45:33.313
Maybe the best position for the
nitrogen is neither to the left

00:45:33.313 --> 00:45:35.869
nor in the middle,
but in between;

00:45:35.869 --> 00:45:39.550
maybe that's the lowest energy.
 

00:45:39.550 --> 00:45:42.929
And that is what resonance is.
 

00:45:42.929 --> 00:45:47.561
Resonance is when you -- the
true structure is in between the

00:45:47.561 --> 00:45:49.260
structures you draw.
 

00:45:49.260 --> 00:45:54.820
So really what it is,
is a failure of the notation.

00:45:54.820 --> 00:45:59.510
Does everybody see how that's
so?

00:45:59.510 --> 00:46:03.474
It's that the notation you use
doesn't show the right

00:46:03.474 --> 00:46:07.286
structure, and when that happens
there's said to be

00:46:07.286 --> 00:46:11.182
"resonance";
although actually all it is is

00:46:11.182 --> 00:46:13.925
that the true structure is a
single minimum,

00:46:13.925 --> 00:46:17.559
not the double minimum you'd
expect from your drawing.

00:46:17.559 --> 00:46:20.639
It's a failure of the way you
draw.

00:46:20.639 --> 00:46:25.123
And notice that for resonance
you use a double headed arrow

00:46:25.123 --> 00:46:28.139
whereas if I back up a second
here --

00:46:28.139 --> 00:46:30.219
equilibrium,
when you have a double minimum,

00:46:30.219 --> 00:46:34.480
there are two arrows,
two different structures.

00:46:34.480 --> 00:46:36.639
So the question is which is it?
 

00:46:36.639 --> 00:46:39.699
Is the real molecule a double
minimum;

00:46:39.699 --> 00:46:43.188
or the real molecules a double
minimum, are there two

00:46:43.188 --> 00:46:44.059
structures?
 

00:46:44.059 --> 00:46:47.730
Or is there in truth only one
structure?

00:46:47.730 --> 00:46:49.150
So you need to choose.
 

00:46:49.150 --> 00:46:53.440
The choice between whether
there's resonance or equilibrium

00:46:53.440 --> 00:46:57.581
must be based on experimental
facts or on a theory that's

00:46:57.581 --> 00:47:02.166
better than Lewis's theory,
to be able to know which is

00:47:02.166 --> 00:47:04.637
true;
something that can distinguish

00:47:04.637 --> 00:47:07.210
between a single and a double
minimum.

00:47:07.210 --> 00:47:11.137
So equilibrium is two arrows,
and there are two structures

00:47:11.137 --> 00:47:14.585
that go back and forth,
and resonance is a single

00:47:14.585 --> 00:47:17.657
structure,
that our notation isn't very

00:47:17.657 --> 00:47:19.039
good at drawing.
 

00:47:19.039 --> 00:47:24.117
So two real species,
or one real species but two

00:47:24.117 --> 00:47:30.601
reasonable formulas we could
draw for it, or that Lewis would

00:47:30.601 --> 00:47:32.329
draw for it.
 

00:47:32.329 --> 00:47:38.818
So really what it is,
resonance is a failure of

00:47:38.818 --> 00:47:45.025
simplistic notation,
and it's associated with

00:47:45.025 --> 00:47:48.130
unusual stability.
 

00:47:48.130 --> 00:47:55.771
Now when I say 'unusual,' that
implies that you know what usual

00:47:55.771 --> 00:47:57.619
stability is.
 

00:47:57.619 --> 00:48:01.369
So compared to what is it
unusual?

00:48:01.369 --> 00:48:05.280
And we'll address that question
later on.

00:48:05.280 --> 00:48:10.068
So let me just give you finally
an example of equilibrium versus

00:48:10.068 --> 00:48:10.980
resonance.
 

00:48:10.980 --> 00:48:13.559
So this, as you'll learn when
you learn functional groups,

00:48:13.559 --> 00:48:16.483
is a carboxylic acid,
and you could have the hydrogen

00:48:16.483 --> 00:48:19.800
attached to this oxygen or it
could be attached to the other

00:48:19.800 --> 00:48:20.420
oxygen.
 

00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:23.429
So these are not just the same
thing upside down.

00:48:23.429 --> 00:48:25.827
It's the hydrogen being
attached to one or being

00:48:25.827 --> 00:48:28.019
attached to the other of the two
oxygens.

00:48:28.019 --> 00:48:31.030
And, in fact, it is that way.
 

00:48:31.030 --> 00:48:34.092
There are two structures and
you go back and forth between

00:48:34.092 --> 00:48:39.360
them;
two species.

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:43.106
But how about if you take the
hydrogen atom away and have this

00:48:43.106 --> 00:48:45.440
thing that's called a free
radical,

00:48:45.440 --> 00:48:49.018
where you don't have a complete
octet on this oxygen?

00:48:49.018 --> 00:48:52.449
There are only two,
four, six, seven electrons

00:48:52.449 --> 00:48:53.059
there.
 

00:48:53.059 --> 00:48:56.030
It has the ability to form
another bond by sharing an

00:48:56.030 --> 00:48:56.659
electron.
 

00:48:56.659 --> 00:49:00.710
Is that two different species?
 

00:49:00.710 --> 00:49:05.829
Or is it one species -- watch
-- with an intermediate geometry

00:49:05.829 --> 00:49:10.360
where you don't really have
double and single bonds but

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:12.460
something in between?
 

00:49:12.460 --> 00:49:14.610
And how do you know which it is?
 

00:49:14.610 --> 00:49:18.030
The only way is to do some
experiment that tells you.

00:49:18.030 --> 00:49:21.434
And there is an experiment that
tells you it's only one nuclear

00:49:21.434 --> 00:49:22.039
geometry.
 

00:49:22.039 --> 00:49:25.331
And we don't have time in the
last thirty seconds to tell you

00:49:25.331 --> 00:49:27.721
how that proof works,
but I'll tell you that the

00:49:27.721 --> 00:49:29.492
technique is electron
paramagnetic resonance

00:49:29.492 --> 00:49:31.139
spectroscopy
&gt;

00:49:31.139 --> 00:49:36.581
, shows that in truth,
although this is two species,

00:49:36.581 --> 00:49:38.929
this is one species.
 

00:49:38.929 --> 00:49:42.170
So there's equilibrium at the
top and resonance at the bottom.

00:49:42.170 --> 00:49:45.827
And if you add an extra
electron to make a carboxylate

00:49:45.827 --> 00:49:49.898
anion, infrared spectroscopy
tells you that it's symmetrical

00:49:49.898 --> 00:49:50.449
too.
 

00:49:50.449 --> 00:49:52.699
There's resonance in this case.
 

00:49:52.699 --> 00:49:55.130
It's an intermediate structure.
 

00:49:55.130 --> 00:49:58.659
But that is "lore."
 

00:49:58.659 --> 00:50:01.230
You didn't predict that from
Lewis structure ahead of time.

00:50:01.230 --> 00:50:03.974
It could've been either way,
and in fact there were many

00:50:03.974 --> 00:50:06.420
people who thought it was one
way or the other.

00:50:06.420 --> 00:50:08.789
It's only experiment that does
it.

00:50:08.789 --> 00:50:11.869
So, next time we'll talk more
about lore.

